Itâ€™s  August 2025, and even now, I still remember herâ€”my first love. We started talking in 2022, and over two years, something real grew between us. At least, thatâ€™s what I believed. We shared countless conversations, late-night thoughts, silly jokes, and quiet moments that made me feel like we had something special. On the night of November 19th, I finally opened up and proposed to her online. She didnâ€™t say yes, but she didnâ€™t shut the door either. She gave me something both beautiful and painful: hope. She told me maybe weâ€™d be in a relationship in 2025. I held onto that for so long. That small hope became something I carried through everythingâ€”the hard days, the lonely nights, the changing years. But today, in August 2025, that hope finally broke. I saw her with someone else. Laughing. Holding hands. Happy. And the worst part? I stood there quietly, watching the girl I once dreamed of building a future with, now living a different storyâ€”one that Iâ€™m not part of. It hurt more than I want to admit. Not because she moved onâ€”I know people grow, change, choose different pathsâ€”but because for so long, I believed that maybe, just maybe, we were still written into each other's futures. She wasnâ€™t just someone I liked. She was the first person I ever truly loved. That kind of love doesn't fade easily. It lingers, even when itâ€™s no longer returned. And while I know I have to move forward, I also know itâ€™s okay to feel the sadness. Itâ€™s okay to miss what couldâ€™ve been. But Iâ€™m also learning that love isnâ€™t just about getting someone in the endâ€”itâ€™s about what that person awakened in you. She taught me how deep I could feel, how much I could care, how brave I could be when Iâ€™m vulnerable. Maybe that was her role in my lifeâ€”not to stay, but to show me what love looks like, even if it wasnâ€™t mine to keep. Sheâ€™ll always be my first love. Not my forever, not my endingâ€”but a part of me Iâ€™ll always remember with both pain and quiet gratitude.
